INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('343','343','1','Apr 7: Euler Strikes Again!  Another Euler\'s Constant','1:00 p.m., Bronfman 106.<br /> <p>Math/Stats Department Colloquium by Teresa Shirkova \'10. We will consider Euler&rsquo;s Constant &gamma; and explore its relationship with the generalization of the factorial function, &Gamma;(x) (known as the Gamma function). Using some clever induction and the notion of logarithmic convexity, we will present a recent proof of the fact that &Gamma;&rsquo;(1) = - &gamma;.</p>','1:00 p.m., Bronfman 106.<br /> <p>Math/Stats Department Colloquium by Teresa Shirkova \'10. We will consider Euler&rsquo;s Constant &gamma; and explore its relationship with the generalization of the factorial function, &Gamma;(x) (known as the Gamma function). Using some clever induction and the notion of logarithmic convexity, we will present a recent proof of the fact that &Gamma;&rsquo;(1) = - &gamma;.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270513220','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('341','341','1','Apr 6: Visual Illusions -- Research at the Intersection of Neuroscience, Psychology, Physics, ...','7:00 p.m., Wege Auditorium, Chemistry 123.<br /> <p>Arthur Shapiro, Associate Professor of Psychology at American University, specializes in the areas of visual perception and cognitive neuroscience. His research concentrates on color, motion, visual camouflage, and low-light-level vision. He is best known for creating a series of visual phenomena (illusions) that have arisen from this research. The illusions elucidate the connections between perception, the brain, and the physical world, and have been regularly recognized in international contests associated with vision science conferences. Many of his illusions can be seen <a href=\"http://www.illusionsciences.com/\" target=\"_blank\">on his demo page, and at his blog</a>.  Sponsored by the Psychology Department Class of 1960 Scholars Program.</p><br /><a href=\'/admin/news/releases/1943/\'>More &raquo;</a>','7:00 p.m., Wege Auditorium, Chemistry 123.<br /> <p>Arthur Shapiro, Associate Professor of Psychology at American University, specializes in the areas of visual perception and cognitive neuroscience. His research concentrates on color, motion, visual camouflage, and low-light-level vision. He is best known for creating a series of visual phenomena (illusions) that have arisen from this research. The illusions elucidate the connections between perception, the brain, and the physical world, and have been regularly recognized in international contests associated with vision science conferences. Many of his illusions can be seen <a href=\"http://www.illusionsciences.com/\" target=\"_blank\">on his demo page, and at his blog</a>.  Sponsored by the Psychology Department Class of 1960 Scholars Program.</p><br /><a href=\'/admin/news/releases/1943/\'>More &raquo;</a>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270513220','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('340','340','1','Apr 6: Chris Martin talks about his paintings','7:00 p.m., Lawrence 231.<br /> <p>Describing New York artist Chris Martin\'s work in the NY Times, Roberta Smith wrote: \"Although he rightfully counts the painters Alfred Jensen and Forrest Bess among his inspirations, his style might be called &rsquo;80s mongrel ... he takes possession of all this by infusing it with his own sense of funky materiality, quasi-psychedelic color and hallucinatory light.\"   Sponsored by the Art Department and the Orrin Simons Fund.</p><br /><a href=\'/admin/news/releases/1939/\'>More &raquo;</a>','7:00 p.m., Lawrence 231.<br /> <p>Describing New York artist Chris Martin\'s work in the NY Times, Roberta Smith wrote: \"Although he rightfully counts the painters Alfred Jensen and Forrest Bess among his inspirations, his style might be called &rsquo;80s mongrel ... he takes possession of all this by infusing it with his own sense of funky materiality, quasi-psychedelic color and hallucinatory light.\"   Sponsored by the Art Department and the Orrin Simons Fund.</p><br /><a href=\'/admin/news/releases/1939/\'>More &raquo;</a>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270513220','0');
