INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('460','460','1','Apr 16: The Zeiss Planetarium Sky','7:30 p.m., Old Hopkins Observatory, 829 Main Street.<br /> <p>Experience the wonders of our universe from the high-precision Zeiss Skymaster ZKP3/B opto-mechanical planetarium projector. Shows last about 50 minutes. For reservations (recommended) contact Barbara Swanson at (413) 597-2188. Others admitted as space permits. Large groups please call for special appointments. <a href=\"/admin/news/releases/1919/\">More...</a></p>','7:30 p.m., Old Hopkins Observatory, 829 Main Street.<br /> <p>Experience the wonders of our universe from the high-precision Zeiss Skymaster ZKP3/B opto-mechanical planetarium projector. Shows last about 50 minutes. For reservations (recommended) contact Barbara Swanson at (413) 597-2188. Others admitted as space permits. Large groups please call for special appointments. <a href=\"/admin/news/releases/1919/\">More...</a></p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('461','461','1','Apr 17: Can and Should Courage and Independence of Mind be Taught?','12:30 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>Robert Gaudino believed that the experience of confronting the other, seeing the world through other people&rsquo;s eyes, and questioning all your assumptions, can produce moral human beings who demonstrate independence of mind and courage on behalf of  principle in the face of contrary pressure in personal and professional life.  And he believed that state of being can and should be taught to young adults in a classroom. Do you agree?   Moderator, Marty Linsky, &rsquo;61.  Panel includes Steve Lewis, &rsquo;60, Ellen Sherberg, &rsquo;70, Alan Schlosser, &rsquo;63, and Pam Carlton, &rsquo;76.  Part of a weekend of Gaudino Fund events.</p>','12:30 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>Robert Gaudino believed that the experience of confronting the other, seeing the world through other people&rsquo;s eyes, and questioning all your assumptions, can produce moral human beings who demonstrate independence of mind and courage on behalf of  principle in the face of contrary pressure in personal and professional life.  And he believed that state of being can and should be taught to young adults in a classroom. Do you agree?   Moderator, Marty Linsky, &rsquo;61.  Panel includes Steve Lewis, &rsquo;60, Ellen Sherberg, &rsquo;70, Alan Schlosser, &rsquo;63, and Pam Carlton, &rsquo;76.  Part of a weekend of Gaudino Fund events.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('462','462','1','Apr 17: Experiential Education: Past, Present, &amp; Future','2:15 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>This panel will include participants in Williams&rsquo; programs over the years, from Gaudino&rsquo;s in-India (Bill Loomis, &rsquo;71) and Guadino@Home (Jeff Thaler, &rsquo;74), to the relatively recent Williams-in-New York, to the very recent &ldquo;Resettling Refugees in Maine&rdquo; project (Bianca Martinez, &rsquo;12 & Charlotte Silverman, &rsquo;10) and the overseas Winter Study experiences from two Gaudino Fellows (Adam Century, &rsquo;12 & Meghan Rose Donnelly, &rsquo;11).  Moderator:  Ed Burger, Professor of Mathematics and Gaudino Scholar.</p>','2:15 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>This panel will include participants in Williams&rsquo; programs over the years, from Gaudino&rsquo;s in-India (Bill Loomis, &rsquo;71) and Guadino@Home (Jeff Thaler, &rsquo;74), to the relatively recent Williams-in-New York, to the very recent &ldquo;Resettling Refugees in Maine&rdquo; project (Bianca Martinez, &rsquo;12 & Charlotte Silverman, &rsquo;10) and the overseas Winter Study experiences from two Gaudino Fellows (Adam Century, &rsquo;12 & Meghan Rose Donnelly, &rsquo;11).  Moderator:  Ed Burger, Professor of Mathematics and Gaudino Scholar.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('463','463','1','Apr 17: Mark Hopkins Today: Professor Gaudinos Impact','3:45 p.m., Brooks Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>A wide range of alumni will give 5-10 minute presentations on the ways in which Prof. Gaudino had a life-long impact on them.  Participants include Matt Nimetz &rsquo;60, Counselor and Undersecretary at the State Dept, and as Personal Envoy for the UN Secretary General; Richard Brockman &rsquo;69, writer whose screenplay \"Good Behavior\" won a screenwriting/playwriting fellowship from the New York Foundation for the Arts.; Michael Morfit &rsquo;68, commissioned Foreign Service Officer with USAID, Vice President of Development Alternatives, Inc, and Visiting Professor and Georgetown University; James Mathieu &rsquo;72, commercial real estate broker with Contour Investment Properties in Jackson Hole, WY.</p>','3:45 p.m., Brooks Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>A wide range of alumni will give 5-10 minute presentations on the ways in which Prof. Gaudino had a life-long impact on them.  Participants include Matt Nimetz &rsquo;60, Counselor and Undersecretary at the State Dept, and as Personal Envoy for the UN Secretary General; Richard Brockman &rsquo;69, writer whose screenplay \"Good Behavior\" won a screenwriting/playwriting fellowship from the New York Foundation for the Arts.; Michael Morfit &rsquo;68, commissioned Foreign Service Officer with USAID, Vice President of Development Alternatives, Inc, and Visiting Professor and Georgetown University; James Mathieu &rsquo;72, commercial real estate broker with Contour Investment Properties in Jackson Hole, WY.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('464','464','1','Apr 17: Collecting the Thoughts of the Day on Great Teaching','4:45 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>A panel on how great teaching can and should change the way students see the world and how they live their lives.  And what it takes for this to happen.  Discussion led by former Gaudino Fund Chair, Richard Herzog, &rsquo;60.</p>','4:45 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>A panel on how great teaching can and should change the way students see the world and how they live their lives.  And what it takes for this to happen.  Discussion led by former Gaudino Fund Chair, Richard Herzog, &rsquo;60.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('465','465','1','Apr 17: From Bandung to Tehran: Transnational Networks in the Postcolonial World','9:00 a.m. - 4:00 p.m., Griffin 3.<br /> <p>A day of panels and talks featuring faculty from Williams, Johns Hopkins, USC, UNC, Ohio State, and Yale.  Free and open to the public.  Sponsored by the Stanley Kaplan Program in American Foreign Policy.  9:00 Panel I: The 1950s.   10:45 Panel II: The 1960s.   1:30 Address by Vijay Prashad, Professor of International Studies, Trinity College  2:30	Panel III: The 1970s. <a href=\"/leadership/events/\">More...</a></p>','9:00 a.m. - 4:00 p.m., Griffin 3.<br /> <p>A day of panels and talks featuring faculty from Williams, Johns Hopkins, USC, UNC, Ohio State, and Yale.  Free and open to the public.  Sponsored by the Stanley Kaplan Program in American Foreign Policy.  9:00 Panel I: The 1950s.   10:45 Panel II: The 1960s.   1:30 Address by Vijay Prashad, Professor of International Studies, Trinity College  2:30	Panel III: The 1970s. <a href=\"/leadership/events/\">More...</a></p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('466','466','1','Apr 20: MCC Canvas Project: Journey Woman','5:00 p.m., Jenness House.<br /> <p>The Williams College Multicultural Center (MCC) hosts an opening reception for the exhibit Journey Woman, on view from April 20-June 20. Helina Metaferia examines themes of identity and personal development through the figure. This exhibition features new mixed media paintings that celebrate spiritual journeys into self-discovery. Helina is the owner and founder of <a href=\"http://www.themetaexperience.com\" target=\"_blank\">The Meta Experience</a>, a visual and healing arts company. Also: artist talk and open meditation at noon in Hardy House. Lunch provided. More information: (413) 596-3340.</p>','5:00 p.m., Jenness House.<br /> <p>The Williams College Multicultural Center (MCC) hosts an opening reception for the exhibit Journey Woman, on view from April 20-June 20. Helina Metaferia examines themes of identity and personal development through the figure. This exhibition features new mixed media paintings that celebrate spiritual journeys into self-discovery. Helina is the owner and founder of <a href=\"http://www.themetaexperience.com\" target=\"_blank\">The Meta Experience</a>, a visual and healing arts company. Also: artist talk and open meditation at noon in Hardy House. Lunch provided. More information: (413) 596-3340.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('467','467','1','Apr 20: Self-Portraiture in 19th-century Istanbul','5:30 p.m., The Clark, 225 South Street.<br /> <p>Clark Fellows Lecture by Clark/Oakley Fellow Mary Roberts, the John Schaeffer Associate Professor of British Art at the University of Sydney. &ldquo;Framings: Self-Portraiture in Nineteenth-Century Istanbul.&rdquo; Clark Fellows Lectures are free. <a href=\"http://www.clarkart.edu/visit/press/content.cfm?ID=3210&year=2010\" target=\"_blank\">More...</a></p>','5:30 p.m., The Clark, 225 South Street.<br /> <p>Clark Fellows Lecture by Clark/Oakley Fellow Mary Roberts, the John Schaeffer Associate Professor of British Art at the University of Sydney. &ldquo;Framings: Self-Portraiture in Nineteenth-Century Istanbul.&rdquo; Clark Fellows Lectures are free. <a href=\"http://www.clarkart.edu/visit/press/content.cfm?ID=3210&year=2010\" target=\"_blank\">More...</a></p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('468','468','1','Apr 20: Feeding our Schoolchildren: Slow Food and the Food Revolution','7:00 p.m., Brooks Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>Joshua Viertel, President of <a href=\"http://www.slowfoodusa.org/index.php/about_us/\" target=\"_blank\">Slow Food USA</a>, has made significant contributions to the sustainable food movement in the past as a teacher, farmer, and activist, and, for the past six years, as a co-founder and co-director of the <a href=\"http://www.yale.edu/sustainablefood/\" target=\"_blank\">Yale Sustainable Food Project</a>. At Yale, Viertel oversaw the University&rsquo;s transition to a local sustainable food program, created and managed an organic farm on campus, and built educational and academic programming around food and agriculture.  Under his leadership, the Yale Sustainable Food Project has earned a reputation as a leader in the national and international sustainable food movement.</p>','7:00 p.m., Brooks Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>Joshua Viertel, President of <a href=\"http://www.slowfoodusa.org/index.php/about_us/\" target=\"_blank\">Slow Food USA</a>, has made significant contributions to the sustainable food movement in the past as a teacher, farmer, and activist, and, for the past six years, as a co-founder and co-director of the <a href=\"http://www.yale.edu/sustainablefood/\" target=\"_blank\">Yale Sustainable Food Project</a>. At Yale, Viertel oversaw the University&rsquo;s transition to a local sustainable food program, created and managed an organic farm on campus, and built educational and academic programming around food and agriculture.  Under his leadership, the Yale Sustainable Food Project has earned a reputation as a leader in the national and international sustainable food movement.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('469','469','1','Apr 22: U.S. Popular Culture in the 19th &amp; 20th Centuries','4:15 p.m., Bernhard Music Center 30.<br /> <p>Lecture by Steve Waksman, associate professor of music and American studies at Smith College. His research and teaching interests are in the history of U.S. popular culture&mdash;especially music, but also film, television, and literature&mdash;during the 19th and 20th centuries, and in the intersection of race, gender and sexuality.He was the keynote speaker at the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame\'s American Music Masters conference honoring Les Paul. And his dissertation on the electric guitar won the Ralph Henry Gabriel Prize awarded by the American Studies Association.</p><br /><a href=\'http://music.williams.edu/node/1155\'>More &raquo;</a>','4:15 p.m., Bernhard Music Center 30.<br /> <p>Lecture by Steve Waksman, associate professor of music and American studies at Smith College. His research and teaching interests are in the history of U.S. popular culture&mdash;especially music, but also film, television, and literature&mdash;during the 19th and 20th centuries, and in the intersection of race, gender and sexuality.He was the keynote speaker at the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame\'s American Music Masters conference honoring Les Paul. And his dissertation on the electric guitar won the Ralph Henry Gabriel Prize awarded by the American Studies Association.</p><br /><a href=\'http://music.williams.edu/node/1155\'>More &raquo;</a>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('470','470','1','Apr 22: Clash of Cartoons: Debates over the Headscarf and Relations with the US in Turkey','7:00 p.m., Griffin 6.<br /> <p>Pinar Batur, the Director of International Studies at Vassar College and John VanderLippe, Associate Dean at the New School for Social Research in New York will speak on he role of metaphors and icons in the rhetorical lexicon of Turkish political discourse. They will focus on political cartoons as image-based narratives of the conflict between secularist and Islamist forces to explore how icons and metaphors have evolved over time in response to the changing political situation in Turkey, and global circumstances. In this context, they will discuss the politics of images of the &ldquo;headscarf&rdquo; debate and Turkish-American relations.</p>','7:00 p.m., Griffin 6.<br /> <p>Pinar Batur, the Director of International Studies at Vassar College and John VanderLippe, Associate Dean at the New School for Social Research in New York will speak on he role of metaphors and icons in the rhetorical lexicon of Turkish political discourse. They will focus on political cartoons as image-based narratives of the conflict between secularist and Islamist forces to explore how icons and metaphors have evolved over time in response to the changing political situation in Turkey, and global circumstances. In this context, they will discuss the politics of images of the &ldquo;headscarf&rdquo; debate and Turkish-American relations.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('471','471','1','Apr 22: Going Rogue: Maverick Leadership in the Arts','7:30 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>This event inaugurates the new Fulkerson Fund for Leadership in the Arts. Opening Remarks by Williams College President Adam Falk.   Featuring: Marit Westermann \'84, Provost, New York University Abu Dhabi, and Vice President Designate, Andrew W. Mellon Foundation; Rick Lowe, artist/founder, Project Row Houses; Susan Sollins, Executive Producer and Curator, art:21, PBS; Joe Thompson \'81, Director, MASS MoCA; Paul Tucker \'72, Professor of the History of Art, UMass Boston, and WCMA Visiting Committee Member. <a href=\"http://www.wcma.org\" target=\"_blank\">WCMA</a></p>','7:30 p.m., Brooks-Rogers Recital Hall.<br /> <p>This event inaugurates the new Fulkerson Fund for Leadership in the Arts. Opening Remarks by Williams College President Adam Falk.   Featuring: Marit Westermann \'84, Provost, New York University Abu Dhabi, and Vice President Designate, Andrew W. Mellon Foundation; Rick Lowe, artist/founder, Project Row Houses; Susan Sollins, Executive Producer and Curator, art:21, PBS; Joe Thompson \'81, Director, MASS MoCA; Paul Tucker \'72, Professor of the History of Art, UMass Boston, and WCMA Visiting Committee Member. <a href=\"http://www.wcma.org\" target=\"_blank\">WCMA</a></p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
INSERT INTO `node_revisions` VALUES ('472','472','1','Apr 22: The Politics of Climate: Building Trust in the New Energy Economy','7:30 p.m., Wege Auditorium, Thompson Chemistry 123.<br /> <p>A lecture by David Moulton, Director of the Climate Policy and Conservation Funding for the Wilderness Society. Moulton played a key role in enabling the passage of the 2007 Energy Act requiring the increase of fuel economy standards for America\'s passenger vehicles by at leat 10 mpg by 2021.  Sponsored as part of Earth Week by the Center for Environmental Studies.</p>','7:30 p.m., Wege Auditorium, Thompson Chemistry 123.<br /> <p>A lecture by David Moulton, Director of the Climate Policy and Conservation Funding for the Wilderness Society. Moulton played a key role in enabling the passage of the 2007 Energy Act requiring the increase of fuel economy standards for America\'s passenger vehicles by at leat 10 mpg by 2021.  Sponsored as part of Earth Week by the Center for Environmental Studies.</p>','Created/updated by FeedsNodeProcessor','1270728728','0');
